  "meta": {
    "title": "Oxygen minimum zone",
    "date": "2026-07-18",
    "lesson": "In parts of the ocean, a thick mid-water layer holds almost no dissolved oxygen — an oxygen minimum zone, formed where sinking organic matter is respired faster than currents can resupply O2. These expanding 'dead zones' are anything but dead to microbes: deprived of oxygen, bacteria switch to breathing nitrate instead, driving denitrification and anammox that strip fixed nitrogen from the sea and release greenhouse nitrous oxide. Sink into the anoxic mid-layer and your metabolism runs on nitrate; the bright oxygenated surface belongs to your aerobic competitors.",
    "citation": "Ulloa et al. (2012), PNAS 109:15996-16003. doi:10.1073/pnas.1205009109",
    "difficulty": "hard",
    "realWorldBasis": "Eastern tropical Pacific oxygen minimum zone"
  },
